Borscht is a tart soup popular in several Eastern European cuisines, 
including Ukrainian, Russian, Polish, Belarusian, Lithuanian and Romanian, 
as well as Ashkenazi Jewish. 



It derives from an ancient soup cooked from pickled common hogweed. 





The variety most commonly associated with the name in English is a beetroot soup of Ukrainian origin; 



other varieties include sorrel, rye, and cabbage borscht. 


Borscht is typically made by combining meat or bone stock with saut√©ed vegetables, 



